            "is_accepted": true,
            "last_activity_date": 1380365885,
            "creation_date": 1380365885,
            "body": "<p>The \"...\" operator accepts arrays, so you could just do the following:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>ArrayList &lt;String&gt; values = someOtherMethod(); \nfunc(values.toArray(new String[values.size()]);\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 19066187,
            "question_id": 19066160
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/ktLZl.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 971196,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 993742,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/993742/isnot2bad",
                "reputation": 24504,
                "display_name": "isnot2bad"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1380366132,
            "creation_date": 1380366132,
            "body": "<p>It's a little bit complex as <code>func<\/code> requires one <code>String<\/code> and then an arbitrary number of additional <code>Strings<\/code>:<\/p>\n\n<pre><code>List&lt;String&gt; values = someOtherMethod();\nif (values.isEmpty()) {\n    // handle special case\n} else{\n    func(values.get(0), values.subList(1, values.size()).toArray(new String[]));\n}\n<\/code><\/pre>\n",
            "answer_id": 19066225,
            "question_id": 19066160
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/hd360.jpg?s=256",
